## Node Types

| Type | Draft Command | Purpose |
|------|--------------|---------|
| `source` | `seeknal draft source <name>` | Load data from CSV, Parquet, JSONL, database, or Python |
| `transform` | `seeknal draft transform <name>` | SQL or Python data transformations |
| `feature_group` | `seeknal draft feature_group <name>` | Feature store with entity, materialization, versioning |
| `model` | `seeknal draft model <name>` | ML model training and serving |
| `aggregation` | `seeknal draft aggregation <name>` | Time-windowed feature aggregations |
| `rule` | `seeknal draft rule <name>` | Data quality checks (not_null, range, freshness, SQL assertion) |
| `profile` | `seeknal draft profile <name>` | Statistical profiling (14+ metrics per column) |
| `semantic_model` | `seeknal draft semantic_model <name>` | Semantic layer for analytics (dimensions, measures) |
| `metric` | `seeknal draft metric <name>` | Business metrics (KPIs, ratios, cumulative) |
| `exposure` | `seeknal draft exposure <name>` | Reports and dashboards |

Add `--python` to draft Python-based nodes: `seeknal draft transform <name> --python`

## Workflow

### 1. Create Nodes

```bash
# Generate a template — edit the YAML to match your data
seeknal draft source customers
# Edit draft_source_customers.yml with your source config
```

### 2. Validate

```bash
seeknal dry-run draft_source_customers.yml
# Shows: schema validation, SQL preview, dependency checks
```

### 3. Apply to Project

```bash
seeknal apply draft_source_customers.yml
# Moves file to seeknal/sources/customers.yml
# Auto-regenerates target/manifest.json
```

### 4. Build & Run

```bash
seeknal plan          # Shows execution order (topological sort)
seeknal run           # Executes all nodes
seeknal run --nodes transform.clean  # Run specific node + upstream
seeknal run --tags etl               # Run nodes with matching tags
seeknal run --full                   # Ignore cache, re-run everything
```

## YAML Schema Discovery

Every `seeknal draft <type> <name>` generates a complete template with all available fields commented. Use this to discover the schema:

```bash
seeknal draft source example_source
cat draft_source_example_source.yml   # See all available fields
rm draft_source_example_source.yml    # Clean up if not needed
```

## SQL References

Use `ref()` to reference upstream nodes in transform SQL:

```yaml
# Positional (order matters):
inputs:
  - ref: source.customers    # → input_0
  - ref: source.orders       # → input_1
transform: |
  SELECT c.*, o.total
  FROM input_0 c
  JOIN input_1 o ON c.id = o.customer_id

# Named (order-safe, self-documenting):
transform: |
  SELECT c.*, o.total
  FROM ref('source.customers') c
  JOIN ref('source.orders') o ON c.id = o.customer_id
```

